{"title_page": "The Catch (baseball)", "text_new": "{{short description|Defensive play made by NY Giant Willie Mays in Game 1 of the 1954 World Series}}\n{{use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{About|the famous baseball catch|other uses|The Catch (disambiguation)}}\n[[Image:The Catch.png|thumb|[[Willie Mays]] catches [[Vic Wertz]]'s deep [[Batted ball|fly ball]] on the [[warning track]] in the [[1954 World Series]].]]\n'''The Catch''' was a [[baseball]] play made by [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] center fielder [[Willie Mays]] on September 29, 1954, during Game 1 of the [[1954 World Series]] at the [[Polo Grounds]] in [[Upper Manhattan|Upper Manhattan, New York City]]. During the eighth [[inning]] with the score tied 2\u20132, [[1954 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]] batter [[Vic Wertz]] hit a deep [[Batted ball|fly ball]] to [[Center fielder|center field]] that was poised to score the [[Base running|runners on base]]. However, Mays made an over-the-shoulder [[Catch (baseball)|catch]] while on the run to record the [[Out (baseball)|out]], and his throw back to the [[Infield#Baseball|infield]] prevented the runners from advancing. The Giants won the game 5\u20132 in [[extra innings]], and eventually the World Series. The Catch is regarded as one of the greatest plays in baseball history.\n\n==The play==\nIn the top of the 8th inning with the score tied 2\u20132,<ref>{{cite news|last=Bahr|first=Chris|title=Flashback: Willie Mays makes 'The Catch' in 1954 World Series|url=http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/willie-mays-catch-1954-world-series-new-york-giants-san-francisco-hall-of-famer-vic-wertz-092915|publisher=[[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]|date=September 29, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> Giants starting [[pitcher]] [[Sal Maglie]] [[base on balls|walked]] Indians lead off hitter [[Larry Doby]]. [[Al Rosen]] singled, putting [[baserunning|runners]] on first and second.<ref name=retrosheet>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1954/B09290NY11954.htm |title=New York Giants 5, Cleveland Indians 2 |website=[[Retrosheet]] |date=September 29, 1954 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref> New York [[manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Leo Durocher]] summoned left-handed [[relief pitcher]] [[Don Liddle]] to pitch to Cleveland's Wertz, a left-handed batter.<ref name=retrosheet/>\n\nWertz worked the count to two balls and one strike before hitting Liddle's fourth pitch approximately {{convert|420|feet|m}} to deep center field. In many stadiums the ball would have been a [[home run]], which would have given the Indians a 5\u20132 lead. However, the Polo Grounds center field was larger than average, and Mays, who was playing in shallow center field, made an on-the-run, over-the-shoulder catch at the [[warning track]] for the out. Having caught the ball, he immediately spun and threw the ball. Doby, the runner on second, might have been able to score the go-ahead run had he tagged at the moment the ball was caught; as it was, he ran when the ball was hit, then had to scramble back to tag. Mays' throw went to second base, holding Cleveland to runners at second and third with one out.<ref name=retrosheet/>\n\nRight-hander [[Marv Grissom]] then relieved Liddle,<ref name=retrosheet/> who supposedly remarked to [[coach (baseball)|coach]] [[Freddie Fitzsimmons]], \"Well, I got ''my'' man.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gcwv4OxWTgIC&lpg=PA99&ots=3rRzP-XHch&pg=PA99#v=onepage&q&f=false |first=Bill |last=Deane |title=Baseball Myths: Debating, Debunking, and Disproving Tales from the Diamond |page=99 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=2012 |isbn=9780810885462 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref> Grissom walked [[pinch hitter]] [[Dale Mitchell (baseball)|Dale Mitchell]] to load the bases, then struck out pinch hitter [[Dave Pope]], and got catcher [[Jim Hegan]] to fly out, ending the inning with no runs scored.<ref name=retrosheet/>\n[[Image:Mays 19540929.JPG|thumb|right|Mays and Polo Grounds center field distance marker.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n|+ Summary \u2013 top of the 8th inning\n! scope=\"col\"| Pitcher<br><small>New York Giants</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Batter<br><small>Cleveland Indians</small>\n! scope=\"col\"| Result<br><small>(outs in bold)</small>\n|-\n|rowspan=2|Maglie (R) || Doby (L) || Walk\n|-\n|Rosen (R) || Single (Doby to second)\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ddf;|Liddle (L) || style=\"background:#ddf;|Wertz (L) || style=\"background:#ddf;|'''Fly out to center''' (Doby to third)\n|-\n|rowspan=3|Grissom (R) || Mitchell (L) || Walk (Rosen to second)\n|-\n|Pope (L) || '''Strike out'''\n|-\n|Hegan (R) || '''Fly out to left'''\n|}\n\n==Broadcast==\n[[Jack Brickhouse]], calling the game on television for [[Major League Baseball on NBC|NBC]], along with [[Russ Hodges]], described Mays' catch to viewers. The audio has been published on [[compact disc|CD]] with the book ''And the Fans Roared'',<ref name=FansRoared>{{cite book |first=Joe |last=Garner |author-link=Joe Garner (author) |others=[[Bob Costas]] (narrator), [[George Foreman]] (foreword) |title=And the Fans Roared: The Sports Broadcasts That Kept Us on the Edge of Our Seats |publisher=[[Sourcebooks]] |location=[[Naperville, Illinois]] |date=2000 |isbn=1570715823 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Fans-Roared-Sports-Broadcasts-Seats/dp/1570715823/}}</ref> and also as accompaniment to the World Series film.\n\n[[Image:T&T Polo Grounds diagram 1951.svg|thumb|right|Diagram of the [[Polo Grounds]] from 1951]]\n\n<blockquote><poem>\n'''Brickhouse''': There's a long drive... way back at center field... way back, back, it is a... Oh my! Caught by Mays!<ref name=FansRoared/>{{rp|16}} The runner on second, Doby, is able to go to third.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=2000 |title=And the Fans Roared [Disc 1] |publisher=Sourcebooks |medium=CD |time=0:52 of Track 5}}</ref> Willie Mays just brought this crowd to its feet with a catch which must have been an optical illusion to a lot of people!<ref name=FansRoared/>{{rp|17}} Boy! [pause] Notice where that 483 foot mark is in center field? The ball itself\u2014Russ, you know this ballpark better than anyone else I know\u2014had to go about 460,{{efn|{{convert|460|feet|m}}}} didn't it?<ref>{{cite AV media |date=2000 |title=And the Fans Roared [Disc 1] |publisher=Sourcebooks |medium=CD |time=1:06 of Track 5}}</ref>\n\n'''Hodges''': It certainly did, and I don't see how Willie did it, but he's been doing it all year.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=2000 |title=And the Fans Roared [Disc 1] |publisher=Sourcebooks |medium=CD |time=1:23 of Track 5}}</ref>\n\n'''Brickhouse''': Willie Mays just made the catch of the day.<ref>{{cite AV media |date=2000 |title=And the Fans Roared [Disc 1] |publisher=Sourcebooks |medium=CD |time=1:30 of Track 5}}</ref>\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nThere is some question of the depth of straight-away center field. Sometimes there was a 475{{efn|{{convert|475|feet|m}}}} sign in center field, sometimes 483{{efn|{{convert|483|feet|m}}}} (as was the case in 1954).<ref name=lowry/> The ballpark was demolished in 1964, and it is unclear what was being measured when. One theory is that 475 was the distance to the front of the clubhouse overhang, and 483 was the distance to the rear wall under the overhang.<ref name=lowry>{{cite book |first=Phil |last=Lowry |title=Green Cathedrals: The Ultimate Celebrations of All 273 Major League and Negro League Ballparks Past and Present |date=February 1992 |publisher=[[Addison-Wesley]] |isbn=0-201-56777-6 |pp=[https://archive.org/details/greencathedralsu0000lowr/page/195 195\u2013201] |url=https://archive.org/details/greencathedralsu0000lowr/page/195 |url-access=registration }}</ref> Regardless, the ball was not hit to the deepest part of center field; where Mays made his catch is estimated by baseball researchers as not more than {{convert|425|feet|m}} from home plate.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Bill |last=Deane |magazine=[[Baseball Digest]] |date=October 2005 |title=Catching up with Vic Wertz's 1954 World Series Drive |url=http://thegloryofbaseball.blogspot.com/2010/10/catch-circa-1954.html |via=The Glory of Baseball |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath and response==\n[[Image:MAYS THE CATCH.JPG|thumb|right|The baseball glove that Willie Mays used in \"the catch\" on display at the [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum]] in 2008.]]\nThe play prevented the Indians from taking the lead and, in the bottom of the 10th, the Giants won the game on their way to sweeping the Series. The Catch is often considered to be one of the best and most memorable plays in the history of baseball because of the difficulty of the play and the importance of the game itself.<ref>{{cite news|last=Axisa|first=Mike|title=Happy 60th Anniversary: Willie Mays makes 'The Catch'|url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/happy-60th-anniversary-willie-mays-makes-the-catch/|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|date=September 29, 2014|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref>\n\nMays himself did not believe \"The Catch\" to be the best defensive play he ever made.<ref>{{cite news |last=Morgan |first=Joe |author-link=Joe Morgan |title=Mays was Mr. Everything |url=http://static.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/morgan_joe/1191373.html |publisher=[[ESPN.com]] |date=May 4, 2001 |accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10876935/not_my_top_catch_mays/ |title=Not My Top Catch \u2013 Mays |newspaper=[[Long Beach Independent]] |location=[[Long Beach, California]] |agency=[[United Press International|UPI]] |date=September 30, 1954 |accessdate=May 9, 2017 |via=newspapers.com}}</ref> In the CD collection ''[[Ernie Harwell]]'s Audio Scrapbook'', issued in 2006,<ref name=Harwell>{{cite book |first=Ernie |last=Harwell |author-link=Ernie Harwell |title=Ernie Harwell's Audio Scrapbook |publisher=AudioBook Publishing, LLC |date=November 15, 2006 |isbn=978-0979212000 |url=https://www.amazon.com/Ernie-Harwells-Audio-Scrapbook-Harwell/dp/0979212006/}}</ref> Mays talks about a running ''bare-handed'' catch he made at [[Forbes Field]] in [[Pittsburgh]] in 1951, in which the Giants' players teased the young rookie by treating him with complete indifference when he returned to the bench.<ref name=Harwell /> Mays also cited a catch he made against the center field wall at [[Ebbets Field]] in [[Brooklyn|Brooklyn, New York]], in which he had to scurry back so fast he did not have time to turn around.<ref name=Harwell />  Other observers have noted that Mays' quick relay throw from deep center field was the most important part of the 1954 play, the catch itself being merely a matter of Mays outrunning the ball.<ref name=Harwell /> \n\nIn 2007, a [[physicist]] calculated that if the temperature had been {{convert|77|F|C}} rather than {{convert|76|F|C}}, the ball would have traveled {{convert|2|in|cm}} farther than it did, and The Catch might not have been completed.<ref name=\"npr\">{{cite news|title=Engineering in the News March 2007 |url=http://www.engr.uiuc.edu/news/archive/index.php?xId=070208640700 |publisher=[[UIUC College of Engineering]] |date=March 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070919035430/http://www.engr.uiuc.edu/news/archive/index.php?xId=070208640700 |archivedate=September 19, 2007 |accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.si.com/vault/2007/03/12/8402407/going-going-green |title=Going, Going Green |first=Alexander |last=Wolff |magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]] |date=March 12, 2007 |via=''Sports Illustrated'' Vault |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.sportingnews.com/baseball/25moments/9.html |title=Baseball's 25 Greatest Moments \u2013 No. 9 The Catch |website=[[The Sporting News]] |date=1999 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991013122825/http://www.sportingnews.com/baseball/25moments/9.html |archive-date=October 13, 1999 |via=archive.org}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.time.com/time/2003/worldseries/moments/7.html |title=World Series Memorable Moments \u2013 No. 7 Willie Mays' Catch |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=2003 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031211102354/http://www.time.com/time/2003/worldseries/moments/7.html |archive-date=December 11, 2003 |via=archive.org}}\n*{{cite newspaper |url=http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/sports/article_ed3ebd38-9969-508b-b346-a1d142c29f02.html |title=Garagiola had bird\u2019s-eye view for Mays\u2019 famous catch |first=John |last=Leptich |newspaper=[[East Valley Tribune]] |location=[[Tempe, Arizona]] |date=May 9, 2007 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/photo-of-day-ii-an-uncommon-angle-on-the-catch-by-willie-mays/ |title=Photo of Day II: An uncommon angle on 'The Catch' by Willie Mays |first=Dayn |last=Perry |publisher=[[CBS Sports]] |date=January 10, 2014 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1vrsg_-dV7Q |title=Willie Mays makes an amazing over-the-shoulder catch |publisher=[[MLB.com]] |via=[[YouTube]] |quote=<small>Willie Mays makes one of the most memorable plays in World Series history with an over-the-shoulder running catch in deep center field during Game 1 of the 1954 World Series</small>}}\n\n{{Navboxes|list1=\n{{Cleveland Indians}}\n{{San Francisco Giants}}\n{{Major League Baseball on NBC}}\n{{Major League Baseball on Mutual}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catch, The}}\n[[Category:New York Giants (NL) postseason]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians postseason]]\n[[Category:1954 Major League Baseball season]]\n[[Category:World Series games]]\n[[Category:September 1954 sports events]]\n[[Category:1954 in sports in New York City]]\n[[Category:Historic baseball plays]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Defensive play made by NY Giant Willie Mays in Game 1 of the 1954 World Series}}\n{{use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{About|the famous baseball catch|other uses|The Catch (disambiguation)}}\n[[Image:The Catch.png|thumb|[[Willie Mays]] catches [[Vic Wertz]]'s deep [[Batted ball|fly ball]] on the [[warning track]] in the [[1954 World Series]].]]\n'''The Catch''' was a [[baseball]] play made by [[San Francisco Giants|New York Giants]] center fielder [[Willie Mays]] on September 29, 1954, during Game 1 of the [[1954 World Series]] at the [[Polo Grounds]] in [[Upper Manhattan|Upper Manhattan, New York City]]. During the eighth [[inning]] with the score tied 2\u20132, [[1954 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland Indians]] batter [[Vic Wertz]] hit a deep [[Batted ball|fly ball]] to [[Center fielder|center field]] that was poised to score the [[Base running|runners on base]]. However, Mays made an over-the-shoulder [[Catch (baseball)|catch]] while on the run to record the [[Out (baseball)|out]], and his throw back to the [[Infield#Baseball|infield]] prevented the runners from advancing. The Giants won the game 5\u20132 in [[extra innings]], and eventually the World Series. The Catch is regarded as one of the greatest plays in baseball history.\n\n==The play==\nIn the top of the 8th inning with the score tied 2\u20132,<ref>{{cite news|last=Bahr|first=Chris|title=Flashback: Willie Mays makes 'The Catch' in 1954 World Series|url=http://www.foxsports.com/mlb/story/willie-mays-catch-1954-world-series-new-york-giants-san-francisco-hall-of-famer-vic-wertz-092915|publisher=[[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]|date=September 29, 2015|accessdate=June 22, 2016}}</ref> Giants starting [[pitcher]] [[Sal Maglie]] [[base on balls|walked]] Indians lead off hitter [[Larry Doby]]. [[Al Rosen]] singled, putting [[baserunning|runners]] on first and second.<ref name=retrosheet>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/1954/B09290NY11954.htm |title=New York Giants 5, Cleveland Indians 2 |website=[[Retrosheet]] |date=September 29, 1954 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref> New York [[manager (baseball)|manager]] [[Leo Durocher]] summoned left-handed [[relief pitcher]] [[Don Liddle]] to pitch to Cleveland's Wertz, a left-handed batter.<ref name=retrosheet/>\n\nWertz worked the count to two balls and one strike before hitting Liddle's fourth pitch approximately {{convert|420|feet|m}} to deep center field. In many stadiums the ball would have been a [[home run]], which would have given the Indians a 5\u20132 lead. However, the Polo Grounds center field was larger than average, and Mays, who was playing in shallow center field, made an on-the-run, over-the-shoulder catch at the [[warning track]] for the out. Having caught the ball, he immediately spun and threw the ball. Doby, the runner on second, might have been able to score the go-ahead run had he tagged at the moment the ball was caught; as it was, he ran when the ball was hit, then had to scramble back to tag. Mays' throw went to second base, holding Cleveland to runners at second and third with one out.<ref name=retrosheet/>\n\nRight-hander [[Marv Grissom]] then relieved Liddle,<ref name=retrosheet/> who supposedly remarked to [[coach (baseball)|coach]] [[Freddie Fitzsimmons]], \"Well, I got ''my'' man.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gcwv4OxWTgIC&lpg=PA99&ots=3rRzP-XHch&pg=PA99#v=onepage&q&f=false |first=Bill |last=Deane |title=Baseball Myths: Debating, Debunking, and Disproving Tales from the Diamond |page=99 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |date=2012 |isbn=9780810885462 |accessdate=May 9, 2017}}</ref> Grissom walked [[pinch hitter]] [[Dale Mitchell (baseball)|Dale Mitchell]] to load the bases, then struck out pinch hitter [[Dave Pope]], and got catcher [[Jim Hegan]] to fly out, ending the inning with no runs scored.<ref name=retrosheet/>\n[[Image:Mays 19540929.JPG|thumb|right|Mays and Polo Grounds center field distance marker.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n|+ Summary 